      <hedline>
        <hl1>Heedless on Oil</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Dan Carsen letter says Aug 2 editorial opposing Senate bill that would open 8.3 acres in Gulf of Mexico to oil drilling is not critical enough</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I don't think that your Aug. 2 editorial ''Delusional Thinking in the Senate'' is critical enough.</p>
        <p>Majorities in both houses of Congress have voted in favor of increasing offshore oil and gas drilling in the name of (supposedly) lowering energy prices.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I don't think that your Aug. 2 editorial ''Delusional Thinking in the Senate'' is critical enough.</p>
        <p>Majorities in both houses of Congress have voted in favor of increasing offshore oil and gas drilling in the name of (supposedly) lowering energy prices.</p>
        <p>In other words, at a point in history when the effects of global warming are becoming apparent even to former skeptics, our elected representatives are enabling industry to get more of two fuels that contribute to global warming.</p>
        <p>If there is even a mathematical chance that our large-scale use of those fuels could render our only planet unlivable, common sense says that we should lessen use of those fuels.</p>
        <p>There is more than a mathematical chance, and the fact that our leaders are now taking steps to increase supplies of those fuels is shameful.</p>
        <p>Dan Carsen  Brookline, Mass.  Aug. 2, 2006</p>
      </block>
